<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?><rss xmlns:dc="http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/" xmlns:content="http://purl.org/rss/1.0/modules/content/" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" version="2.0"><channel><title><![CDATA[Untitled RSS Feed]]></title><description><![CDATA[Untitled RSS Feed]]></description><link>http://github.com/dylang/node-rss</link><generator>RSS for Node</generator><lastBuildDate>Mon, 12 Aug 2019 09:14:01 GMT</lastBuildDate><item><title><![CDATA[CircleCI: Avoiding failed builds on GitHub Pages branch]]></title><description><![CDATA[My latest project was to reimplement my personal webpage with GatsbyJS.  In the end, it was awesome (and deserves a proper post).  Just aâ€¦]]></description><link>https://robertowm.github.io/posts/2019-04-29-circleci-and-gh-pages-how-to-avoid-failed-builds-on-github-pages-branch/</link><guid isPermaLink="false">https://robertowm.github.io/posts/2019-04-29-circleci-and-gh-pages-how-to-avoid-failed-builds-on-github-pages-branch/</guid><pubDate>Mon, 29 Apr 2019 08:49:36 GMT</pubDate><content:encoded>&lt;p&gt;My latest project was to reimplement my personal webpage with GatsbyJS.  In the end, it was awesome (and deserves a proper post).  Just a quick summary of this project, it relies on NetlifyCMS to manage my page and posts.  All data is stored on GitHub as static files.  In the end, I decided to use CircleCI to implement Continuum Delivery - every time a change happens on the dev branch, it starts a job to build my webpage and push the compiled project to master branch.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;After spending some time configuring CircleCI configuration file, everything was working nicely... expect when things go to the master branch - I started receiving alerts by email related to building failures...&lt;/p&gt;
